<h2 id="discussion">Discussion</h2>
<ul>
<li>Many more clashing forms can be found in papyri due to pronunciation
and misspellings (e.g.&nbsp;πόλεις/πόλις) and not writing out the iota
subscript (sometimes adscript is used, also hypercorrectly).</li>
<li>vocative in documentary papyri: still in use occasionally, but often
replaced by the nominative, as was quite common in Classical Greek as
well.</li>
<li>local endings are occasionally used in documentary papyri, although
they are not numerous. For example, αὐτόθεν (autóthen) <em>from the same
place</em> is found ca. hundred times, οἴκοθεν (oíkothen) <em>from the
house/home</em> 35 hits (most from the 6th century CE), ὁπόθεν
(hopóthen) <em>whencesoever</em> 2 hits, οἴκαδε (oíkade) <em>to
home</em> 2 hits)</li>
<li>use of cases goes into new directions in time, e.g.&nbsp;the genitive and
dative can replace one another (&gt; syntax, use of cases?)</li>
<li>Merger of 1st and 3rd declension was very significant for the
development of the declension system in Medieval and Modern Greek <span class="citation" data-cites="horrocks2010">Horrocks (2010)</span>,
p.&nbsp;120–121.</li>
</ul>
